We know that the $n$th term of a geometric sequence is given by $r^{n-1}a$, where $a$ is the first term and $r$ is the common ratio.  We are given that the fifth term is 11, so we can write $r^4a=11$.  We are also given that the eleventh term is 5, so we can write $r^{10}a=5$.  Dividing the second equation by the first, we obtain $r^6=\frac{5}{11}$.  Taking the sixth root of both sides, we have $r=\sqrt[6]{\frac{5}{11}}=\sqrt[3]{\frac{\sqrt{5}}{11}}$.  We can now plug this value of $r$ into the equation $r^4a=11$ to solve for $a$: \begin{align*}
\left(\sqrt[3]{\frac{\sqrt{5}}{11}}\right)^4a&=11\\
\Rightarrow\qquad\frac{\sqrt{5}}{11}a&=11\\
\Rightarrow\qquad a&=11\sqrt{5}
\end{align*}The eighth term is then $r^7a=\left(\sqrt[3]{\frac{\sqrt{5}}{11}}\right)^7\cdot 11\sqrt{5}=\boxed{\sqrt[3]{5}\cdot11\sqrt{5}}$.
